Rating: 3
This cake turned out perfectly. Just remember to use cake flour (sifted) and it won't be too dry or dense. Penseys crystalized ginger worked great. The fact that it is not overly sweet is a plus.

Rating: 4
I made this cake for my mother's 60th birthday surprise party. It was amazing. After reading some of the reveiws I opted to add 1/2 cup sour cream to the buttermilk to make the cake moist. It was very dense but had a great texture. I also put the ginger in my grinder because I didn't want to chop it. It was sticky but mixed in well and gave the cake an excellent flavor. I used a lemon cream cheese frosting. It was a huge hit. (kids didn't like it much, slightly spicy).

Rating: 3
This is my favorite birthday cake. Like other reviewers, I find the cake a bit dry. Adding an additional 1/4 cup of sour cream and 2 tablespoons of grated fresh ginger help moisten the cake and lift the ginger taste. Our friends love that the resulting cake is not too sweet, but very rich, beautiful (especially with lots of lit candles) and delicious. Serve with a glass of Washington's sparkler - Mountain Dome. Cheers!

Rating: 3
I've made this several times, and it's always well-received. One popular variation I do is to make a bittersweet chocolate frosting instead of the cream cheese one. The Joy of Cooking has a good chocolate ganache I used last time. The crystalized ginger makes a nice garnish for this too.

Rating: 4
I have made this cake three times now, and absolutely love it. 30 minutes was too long---mine was baked in just under 25 minutes. The frosting is out of sight. Since crystallized ginger is fairly expensive, I used about 2/3 of the amount called for, and it turned out well. Will make this one again and again.

Rating: 2
This cake has good flavor but turned out too dry. The frosting is delicious, though--I'm saving the rest for a carrot cake. Nice change from the regular cream cheese frosting.

